                                                                                             5.10 Unauthenticated Reject Message Behavior

                                                                                             In the presence of illegitimate messages with the ability to deny network access, a possible
                                                                                             mitigation is for the UE to continue to search for other available networks while ignoring the
                                                                                             network denying service. The baseband firmware could be tested to understand the behavior
                                                                                             these systems exhibit when in the presence of unauthenticated reject messages. Additional
This publication is available free of charge from: https://doi.org/10.6028/NIST.SP.800-187




                                                                                             research and development is needed to ensure that baseband processors are exhibiting behavior
                                                                                             that does not cause unintentional DoS when receiving an illegitimate reject message.
                                                                                             Addresses the following threats: 4.2.4


                                                                                             5.11 Physical Security of Cell Site Equipment

                                                                                             Physical security of cellular equipment is important to prevent intentional and unintentional
                                                                                             incidents affecting availability. 3GPP TS 33.401 standard mentions “physically protected”
                                                                                             systems and interfaces, underscoring the need for such protections, but does not go on to
                                                                                             describe what actual physical security controls should be put in place. However, the Physical and
                                                                                             Environmental Protection control family from NIST SP 800-53 is a reasonable list of controls to
                                                                                             use as a starting point [33]. The National Public Safety Telecommunications Council (NPSTC)
                                                                                             also describes physical access controls that are useful for securing cellular sites in the context of
                                                                                             public safety [34]. For instance, the document suggests that fences and gates should be locked,
                                                                                             and that detection methods such as video surveillance should be implemented.
                                                                                             Addresses the following threats: 4.7


                                                                                             5.12 Rogue Base Station Detection

                                                                                             As previously stated, rogue base stations can compromise the security of cellular devices and
                                                                                             associated equipment. It is possible to detect the presence of these rogue base stations, although
                                                                                             some may consider this technology still in developmental stages. Mobile applications can be
                                                                                             used to detect the presence of rogue base stations, although using specific chipsets on older
                                                                                             device models are often required [35]. Different approaches can be used for detection purposes.
                                                                                             One method is to receive the information contained within broadcast messages originating from
                                                                                             base stations, and checking that information against known-good values. Another method is to
                                                                                             store lists of known base stations, and alert users when new base stations are identified. In this
                                                                                             situation, it is up to the user to make the final determination. Turnkey solutions are also available
                                                                                             for purchase that will detect the presence of rogue base stations. Either technology has
                                                                                             limitations and may provide false positives, but this is an active area of research that may assist
                                                                                             organizations concerned about the presence of rogue base stations.
                                                                                             Addresses the following threats: 4.2.1, 4.2.2, 4.2.3, 4.2.4




